    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-10-22T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-10-22T03:00:00-05:00" n="234"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d234">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/11253: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-10-22T16:00:00+08:00"
                            >October 22, 1930—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received October 22—11 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>920. 1. Following from the American Consul at Nanking: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“October 21, noon. Ministry of Foreign Affairs sent a representative this
                            morning to inform me that Kian, Kiangsi, is in the hands of bandits and
                            that such Americans as may be in Kian should withdraw at once to places
                            of safety if it is possible for them to do so. The Ministry stated that
                            Kiangsi provincial troops are now en route to Kian to attack the bandits
                            there. I gather that the Ministry fears that the attack by Government
                            troops upon Kian may endanger any Americans there. The Ministry is of
                            the opinion that quick telegraphic notification to Americans in Kian is
                            necessary. Hankow informed.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>2. Legation is instructing Adams to urge the Ministry of Foreign Affairs to take
                    steps for the release at the earliest possible moment of the Filipino Sister
                    taken by bandits at Kian. (See Hankow’s October 21, 3 p.m.)</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
